p: To analyze viral replication in mosquitoes in vivo, we fed female Culex tritaeniorhynchus mosquitoes with pig blood mixed with 8x10 6 focus forming units (ffu) of GIII or GI JEVs. We determined the infection rate by detection of viral titer in each mosquito 14 days post-infection (DPI). GIII CH1392 virus and GI TC2009-1 virus had higher infectious rates (58.33% and 66.67%) than GIII T1P1 virus and GI YL2009-4 virus (25.00% and 16.67%) whereas no genotypic differences were observed in infectivity or in viral titer among positive mosquitoes ( Fig 2). These in vitro and in vivo results suggest that the Culex tritaeniorhynchus mosquito vector may play a minor role in genotype replacement.
